<h3>
    <strong>1. Upper Rogue River (Shady Cove to Lost Creek Dam)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Spring Chinook (Springers) run from <strong>May to July</strong>, offering some of the best wild Chinook action on the Rogue
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Bank access</strong> available at Cole Rivers Hatchery, McGregor Park, and Casey State Recreation Site near Medford
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Boat or drift fishing</strong> is popular in this stretch, especially for early-season back‑bouncing egg rigs&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>2. Middle Rogue (Grants Pass, Gold Hill area)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Prime for <strong>Fall Chinook</strong> from <strong>August through September</strong>, and some <strong>Coho</strong> into October 
    </li>
    <li>
        Bank and drift routes include Valley of the Rogue State Park to Coyote Evans Wayside, or drifting from Griffin Park to Robertson Bridge 
    </li>
    <li>
        Good <strong>spinners and roe rigs</strong> produce action in varied water types&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>3. Lower Rogue (Near Agness and Rogue Bay)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Fall Chinook, Coho, and early <strong>summer steelhead</strong> congregate in late summer and early fall before heading upriver
    </li>
    <li>
        Access from <strong>Agness area</strong>, including gravel bars near towns, and boat-based fishing near the estuary
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>4. Applegate River / Fish Hatchery County Park</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        More focused on <strong>steelhead</strong>, but salmon (especially Coho in fall runs) can appear in late season 
    </li>
    <li>
        Family‑friendly access and shaded creek areas make this a scenic choice for mixed species fishing
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>5. TouVelle State Recreation Site &amp; Sewer Hole</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Located about 9 miles north of Medford, this stretch is easy‑access for fishermen fishing steelhead and spring Chinook arriving in early season
    </li>
    <li>
        Sewer Hole (near Cole Rivers Hatchery effluent) holds marked hatchery returns and is popular for both drift and fly anglers&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
